
The Nexus 7 is an upcoming Android tablet co-developed by Google and Asus, the first tablet entry in the Nexus series. The Nexus 7 is a 7-inch tablet, primarily competing with similar devices such as Amazon's Kindle Fire.
The Nexus 7 was unveiled at Google I/O on June 27, 2012 for release by mid-July, and became immediately available for pre-order through Google Play the same day, starting at $199 USD for a 8GB model.

==Development==

In an interview in December 2011 with an Italian newspaper, Google's Eric Schmidt had confirmed that the company would unveil a tablet within 6 months, owing to increased competition between the company and Apple. While Schmidt did not specifically refer to it as such, it was inferred to be a Nexus device.[tpl]cite web|title=Nexus Tablet Expected Within 6 Months|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/246539/nexus_tablet_expected_within_6_months.html|publisher=PC World|accessdate=18 June 2012[/tpl] By May 2012, information and benchmarks began to leak about the tablet[tpl]emdash[/tpl]revealing that it would be an Asus-produced device refereed known as the "Nexus 7", which would have a 7-inch screen, a quad-core Tegra 3 processor, and version 4.1 of Android.[tpl]cite web|title=Google Nexus 7 Tablet Shows Up on Benchmark Site|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/256519/google_nexus_7_tablet_shows_up_on_benchmark_site.html|publisher=PC World|accessdate=18 June 2012[/tpl]  
Google officially unveiled the Nexus 7 at its I/O developers conference in San Francisco on June 27, 2012. The device is intended to take advantage of the content available through web services such as Google Play[tpl]emdash[/tpl]including e-books. magazines, media, and apps.[tpl]cite web|title=Google Unveils Nexus 7 Tablet for $199|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052702304058404577492760881761278.html|publisher=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=27 June 2012[/tpl]

==Design==

===Software===

The Nexus 7 will be shipped with the latest version of Android, 4.1, codenamed Jelly Bean. Additionally, it will also ship with Chrome as its web browser.[tpl]cite web|title=Google I/O 2012 Keynote Overview: Nexus 7 Tablet, Android 4.1, Nexus Q Media Streamer, and Project Glass|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/258415/google_io_2012_keynote_overview_nexus_7_tablet_android_41_nexus_q_media_streamer_and_project_glass.html|publisher=PC World|accessdate=27 June 2012[/tpl] 

===Hardware===

The Nexus 7 features a 7-inch 1280x800 pixel display, a quad-core Nvidia Tegra 3 processor with a 12-core graphics chip, and support for Bluetooth, NFC, and Wi-Fi.[tpl]cite web|title=Tegra 3 Powering Google Nexus Tablets|url=http://www.nvidia.com/object/nexus-7.html|publisher=NVIDIA|accessdate=27 June 2012[/tpl]

